======================================================================
PART 1: Euler characteristic at n=5 (exhaustive)
======================================================================
n=5: chi (from Betti) distribution: {np.int64(0): 304, np.int64(1): 720}
n=5: chi (from Omega dims) distribution: {0: 304, 1: 720}

======================================================================
PART 2: Euler characteristic at n=6 (exhaustive)
======================================================================
n=6: chi (Betti) distribution: {np.int64(0): 5120, np.int64(1): 27648}
n=6: chi (Omega) distribution: {0: 5120, 1: 27648}

======================================================================
PART 3: Omega Euler char interpretation
======================================================================
For exact sequences: chi(chain complex) = alternating sum of dims
Since d^2 = 0, chi(Omega) = sum(-1)^p dim(Omega_p) = sum(-1)^p beta_p
Wait — they should be equal! That's the rank-nullity theorem.
Let me verify...
  n=5: chi(Betti) = chi(Omega) for ALL 1024 tournaments (as expected)
  n=6: chi(Betti) = chi(Omega) for ALL 32768 tournaments (as expected)

